<p><em>8. MASTER PAGES </em></p>

<p><b>Master Pages</b>
</p><p>
Any text or object that you place on the master page will appear on the entire document pages to which the master is applied. 
Master Pages commonly contain repeating logos, page numbers, headers, and footers. 
They also contain non-printing layout guides, such as column guides, ruler guides, and margin guides.
</p><p>
A master item cannot be selected on a document page.
You can create, modify, and delete objects on master pages just like any other objects, 
but you must do so from the master pages themselves.
</p><p>
<figure class="figure">
<img src="/img/masterPageIcon.jpg" class="float-end img-fluid ps-2 pb-2" width="auto" height="auto" alt="masterPageIcon" />
<figcaption class="figure-caption ps-2 text-danger"> Master Page Icon </figcaption>
</figure>
</p><p>
 
<b>Inserting Page Numbers in Master Pages</b>
</p><p>
To make page numbers appear on every page
</p><p>
1. Click on Master Pages icon. <br>
2. Then click on Text Tool. Now the cursor changes to I - beam.<br>
3. Then click on the left Master page where you want to put the page number.<br>
4. Press Ctrl + Alt + P.<br>
5. The page number displays as ‘LM’ on the left Master Page.<br>
6. Similarly click on the right Master page where you want to put the page number.<br>
7. Press Ctrl + Alt + P.<br>
8. The page number displays as ‘RM’ on the right Master Page, but will appear correctly on the actual pages.
</p><p>
  <code>To specify the starting page number or numbering system:</code>
  </p><p>
1. Choose File > Document Setup<br>
2. To start pagination at a certain number type the starting page in Start Page #.<br>
</p><p>
<code>To specify the numbering system</code>
</p><p>
1. Choose File > Document Setup<br>
2. Click numbers.<br>
3. Select the numbering system you want to use, and then click OK.<br>
</p><p>
 <b>Hiding and Showing Master Page Palette</b>  
</p><p>
  1. To show master page palette, then choose View > Display Master items (which is usually ticked).<br>
  2. To hide master page palette, then choose Window> Show Master Pages in the menu bar. The Master Pages Palette appears.
  </p><p>
  <figure class="figure">
<img src="/img/masterPagePalette.jpg" class="float-end img-fluid ps-2 pb-2" width="auto" height="auto" alt="masterPagePalette" />
<figcaption class="figure-caption ps-2 text-danger"> Master Page Palette </figcaption>
</figure>
</p><p>
 <b>To create a Master Page</b>
</p><p>
Master Pages can be created from scratch, based on existing master pages or from the
guides and specification set on individual pages.
</p><p>
<code>To make from scratch:</code>
</p><p>
1. Window > Master Pages <br>
2. New Master Page... from the master page palette pop-up menu<br>
3. Type in name<br>
4. Set the margins, columns and space between<br>
5. Click OK button
</p><p>
<code>From an existing master page</code>
</p><p>
1. Window > Master Pages<br>
2. Select master page to be duplicated<br>
3. Click Duplicate master... from the master page palette menu and type a name for your master page.<br>
4. Click Duplicate button<br>
4. New master page will appear, edit as required.<br>
</p><p>
<code>From an existing page</code>
</p><p>
1. Turn to the publication page you want to make a new master page<br>
2. Window > Master Pages<br>
3. Save Page As from the master page palette menu<br>
4. Type in name<br>
6. Click Save button
</p><p>
  <b>APPLYING MASTER PAGES</b>
  </p><p>
A new master page has no effect until it is applied to the specific pages. The Document
Master is applied to all pages in your initial publication.
</p><p>
<code>To apply master pages</code>
</p><p>
1. Turn to the page you want to apply the master page<br>
2. Window > Master Pages<br>
3. Click on the master page name or icon and it is applied<br>
</p><p>
<code>To apply on selected pages</code>
</p><p>

1. Window > Master Pages<br>
2. Click to your selected master page<br>
3. Go to palette pop-pu menu, click apply<br>
4. In apply master, type page number in page range Eg., 4-10<br>
5. Click apply button<br>

 </p><p>
<code>To delete</code>
</p><p>
1. Window > Master Pages<br>
2. Select the master page<br>
3. Click Delete Icon...<br>
4. Click OK to confirm<br>

</p><p>
